                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Fian2 wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Sebilis (and other light blue zones) - Great place to charm.  If your hasted charm pet attacks you, it is not that difficult to mez him and his friend, and recharm before they eat through your rune.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
When I was in Seb, it was dark blue.  I would charm a wizard (wizards pets where good DPS! and I could gain mana back on charm breaks with ToT) or shaman (wee, pet that slowed) while I mezzed on most pulls.  Pulling less than 3 would cause me to tell the puller to stop slacking.  I delt with charm breaks.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">edit</span>: I returned to Seb at L 63 or so.  Took out Beckon and almost cleared Juggs before I let a mob run, and died.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">BoT - My best experience charming.  On one occasion, both myself and a magician had charmed, snared pets and we tore through the content.  Killing the named mob was so easy and fast.  On other occasions I have been known to charm an unhasted mob to help with dps for a specific fight.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I've soloed a named (not a wing boss, a named) for shits and giggles.  Took 8 attempts including 5 deaths because charm broke or something else didn't go absolutely perfect.  Usually I'd charm a caster mob or a giant elemental.  When I was hunting there, mobs where dangerous enough that I didn't haste or equip my pets, unless I had backup crowd control and snare.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">LDON Normal - Was way too stressful trying to do cc in Guk along with managing a charmed pet.  The DPS gain was not that useful.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I grab a LDoN normal pet haste it and DW it, and deal with it solo.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">LDON Hard - I am not that stupid.  (:</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
My first successful LDoN hard was with a snared, hasted, 36% item hasted, DWing beast.  We had a paladin or bard permaCCing the pet, and a backup slower.
<br />

<br />
Now I charm non-hasted non-equiped LDoN hard mobs: the extra danger from equipping/hasting isn't worth it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Vxed/Tipt - Every single time I have done this, the group has failed.  We manage to kill for a while, but then charm breaks at a bad time or an add attacks us in the back and the group wipes.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
With a snarer, I can control any of the 3 good-charm models with an average of 1 or 2 deaths per run, geared/buffed to the max.
<br />

<br />
I have semi-reliably killing craigmommy with a cleric and a 2 box ranger.  Based off the hail mary strategy (pray we make it to criagy before we wipe)
<br />

<br />
My first Tipt run was with a cleric, ranger and another enchanter.  4 people.  Took us 8-9 hours to do it successfully.
<br />

<br />
I prefer to use tank/pet/snarer/cleric groups now, they are reliable and quick.  Record is 90 minutes to being ready to engage boss.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">PoV - I could charm worms and then run to exit when charm breaks.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I soloed PoV golems for about 50 AA before I got tired of soloing.
<br />

<br />
I was back to PoV once after it opened up.  I was tanking the golems whie charm-duoing and feeding nearly dead mobs to a friend's younger character's group for shits and giggles.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">HoH - Had a lot of problems here (trying to solo or duo)</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Before the rule of 4, we killed a few named (L 66) in HoH and got some specs.  After the rule of 4, I duoed with a ranger some here, mainly in south shrine.  Used charm pets on R'Dar.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Tactics - Had one successful group that included 2 enchanters (one charmed mob) 1 cleric and 1 druid.  Attempts to solo charm here were not pretty.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Before the CoD nerf, I used to solo Diakus with no snare.  Charm a mob without debuffing, /pet attack, haste it, slow other mob, pray it lasted long enough.  Died alot, but after 96% rez from a friend would come out ahead.  Also did some charm-kite groups with a druid/shaman/etc after the charm nerf.  Tried to single group some of the named and failed.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Based on this, if they think that charm is too much power, I would recommend reducing dps if the mob is snared.  Beyond that, the fear of charm breaks would prevent most enchanters from even considering an attempt to charm something that is a 1k+ hitter.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
AFK bard playing mez on the pet also reduces risk to nearly zero -- or a paladin with a long attention span.  There are too many ways to mitigate charm risk to nearly zero for the reward to diverge with NPC DPS in an uncontrollable manner.
<br />

<br />
I know why charm has to be nerfed.  What I object to is nerfing the DPS it generates while leaving the risk full-bore.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Yakk on Fri Sep 24, 2004 5:58 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
