                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree with you Fian.
<br />

<br />
The skills that make charm "over-powered" take preparation, work and knowledge and are not available to the average player.  People who have mastered those skills have earned the benefits they bring.  Other classes who envy the results of those skills have no idea of the cost.
<br />

<br />
I am an old-fashioned enchanter who leveled when Kunark was just discovered when a chanter was the Master of Crowd Control.  I didn't enjoy charming and never used it until level 60ish.  By this time I was experiencing what others have described . . . that my old crowd control job in groups had been rendered superfluous by lull-pullers who could always bring singles to camp.  And in raid situations it was usually faster and easier to off-tank mobs than to mez them.  People were citicizing me for slowing down our progress by mezzing things. . . that taunting just wasted time when off-tanking would kill them faster.
<br />

<br />
So I decided to redefine my role and learn to charm.  Set this as a personal progression goal.  Other people in my guild assured me that this would make me an asset where just mezzing was a hindrance.  Talked about how much charming would help like using Wrulons against RyAddar or pookas in Vxed and Tipt.
<br />

<br />
Plane of Nightmares -- this is where I began my lessons.  Treant Valley because the treants move very slowly and there is lots of kiting room.  Then moving over to the waterfall to learn how to both handle a charmed mob and adds at the same time.  Then to werewolves.  I was many levels too high to be fighting in PoN.  Still ran screaming to the zone-out many many times until I started to master the basic skills of how to manage pet breaks, toggle between pet and enemy, spells to put in line-up, etc.
<br />

<br />
Luclin -- I used my VT key quest as charm practice.  Did most of the shard camps either solo or duo or trio with a few guildmates and always used charm.  Luclin mobs are much harder than the ones in PoN because they have so many hit points.  When you solo, it is quite likely that the charm will break before the other mob is dead.   So definitely need to haste the pet and equip it every way possible and learn to survive the breaks.  Began to learn how to use other classes to assist on charming:  ranger or druid to snare, mage or shaman to malo.  Duo with a necro is "fun" because they like to dot everything.  Tried this in Maiden's Eye, where I had to root park rather than mez and my necro friend's dots made the target die fast while I was busy rooting/mezzing about a million adds.  Charm is not the tool of choice in Luclin but it is the ONLY way I could solo some of those shard camps and otherwise would have had to ask others to farm my shards for me instead of contributing fully to our farming groups.  I don't feel charm was over-powered.  Solo I was always at risk and duo situations were still sometimes dicey.  Some other classes like mages could farm those camps easily solo with their pets.
<br />

<br />
BoT:  My guild frequently raids BoT towers and with our supremely skilled bard pullers we don't get adds often and with our shamen my slows are frequently unneeded.  Everyone smiled and cheered the day I started charming elementals on these raids.  It was tough at first.  Breaks came often, I got hit and so did the healers.  AAs really make a tremendous difference in the ability to maintain a charm and survive a break.  Once I broke 100 AAs, with many many of those going to protection abilities like Eldritch Rune and Lightning Reflexes, as well as Total Domination, it began to get much less risky.  Now I can easily grab and maintain an elemental pet during a tower run, and usually recharm without much assistance.  And have taught the raid force how to support me by snaring and maloing  my pet and throwing a regen on me when it breaks.  This feels like a fair RvsR equation to me, not over-powered.  Just lets me contribute to the victory.
<br />

<br />
LdoN Normal:  At this level of ability I am also able to effectively control a pet in normal groups...similar risks to BoT.  I like to pull in normals, where paci-pulling singles is easy; if we have a bard or ranger who wants to pull then no crowd control is needed and just slowing/nuking is boring so I charm also.  It feels balanced to me and no complaints from the groups.
<br />

<br />
Halls of Honor:  This is my newest training grounds.  I am slowly and painfully mastering the art of charm solo/duo/trio with these harder hitting mobs.  The difference is in the previous zones I could survive quite a few hits and channel a WoM or mez or root.  These I can't; if they land a few I am down.  My kiting skills need work.  I can go into HoH as a trio grouped with a ranger and cleric and we make out very well when my ability to control the pet is supported by others who can help me with breaks by snaring, healing, rooting, stunning or off-tanking.  Solo I am either dying or having to gate out at 10% health every few mobs.  But I am improving and I know other chanters can solo here effectively...just takes more practice on my part.  Very nice exp makes this worth the effort.  I do not feel this is over-powered . . . I see bards and wizards and druids quad-kiting these mobs all the time and I don't think I have an unfair advantage.
<br />

<br />
Vxed/Tipt:  some of the most skilled fighters in my guild wanted to do the trials in Vxed and Tipt and pressured me to join in.  We were successful . . . but it took a whole group's full-time attention to control the pet and I am aware that I was supported at every step by others.  So a bard who knew the zone cold pulled me an appropriate pet . . . Shaman maloed that pet . . . ranger snared it.. Then I charmed it.  We had a paladin tank who could keep aggro with stuns.  And a cleric to heal.   The pally was MT but the pet did most of the dps.  The bard kept spamming mez on that pet every step of the way in case of a break.  I bought special negative magic resistance weapons to equip that pet as well as some mage toys.  I did not haste it.  And even with all this care we wiped a few times.  We used that pooka like a team of handlers trying to reposition a missile launcher...aimed it at a target...fired.  Target went down.  And yes we completed trials in both Vxed and Tipt this way.  I am fully aware that I could not do this on my own . . . that I was being totally supported in the pooka control by the hawk-like attention of 5 other top-notch players.  I know that the pally was envious of the dps this pet put out and called it "sick."  I would agree this is unbalanced and if it were common and not just a special feature of two specific zones would not be good for the game.  However would point out that that pet dps was generated not my myself alone, but by the whole group of 6 who were needed to manage it.
<br />

<br />
LDoN hard:  This was the next step in my "charm challenge" program.  Haven't tried it yet.  From what I hear, it is like HoH but in close quarters with unsnareable mobs.
<br />

<br />
Plane of Tactics pit:  This was the second next step in my "charm challenge" progream.  From what I hear, this is like PoN because of the adds but the mobs hit like the ones in HoH.
<br />

<br />
In Sum:  I have spent months buying AAs, practicing skills, spending DKP to get gear with foci like Spell Haste and Extended Range, acquiring special tools like Goblin Gauzi ring and Blue Ceramic band . . .all so I can become a better charmer . . . all so I can be an asset to my guild and my groups.
<br />

<br />
Not so I can be uber.  Simply so I can be useful.
<br />

<br />
Now this charm nerf makes more than 6 months of work developing my toon worthless.
<br />

<br />
I am beyond disgusted.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Newar Chrysalis </span>
<br />
Xev - Coercer - Jewelcrafter
<br />
Officer: Povar Tarew Alliance
<br />

<br />
